# forjd-ui is the source of UI primitives

When adding a **component** or **typography** style to the frontend app, add it to `frontend/libs/forjd-ui/` in the same change (or immediately before the app consumes it). Do not leave reusable UI only in `frontend/src/`.

## What belongs in forjd-ui
- Standalone Angular components used (or likely reused) across routes/pages
- Buttons, inputs, badges, layout shells, and other primitives
- Typography scales, text styles, and shared type tokens (prefer `--fj-*` / library SCSS)
- Shared visual patterns that are not page-specific composition

## What may stay in the app
- Route/page shells and feature composition that wire library primitives together
- One-off layout that is clearly single-page and not a reusable control
- App-only data wiring, stores, and API clients

If unsure whether something is reusable, put it in forjd-ui.

## Required checklist (same change set)
1. Create the primitive under `frontend/libs/forjd-ui/src/lib/<name>/` (e.g. `ng generate component` in the library).
2. Export it from `frontend/libs/forjd-ui/src/public-api.ts`.
3. Add a colocated `*.stories.ts` Storybook story.
4. Consume it from the app via the library public API — do not duplicate markup/styles in the app.
5. Prefer FJORD tokens (`--fj-*`) over ad-hoc colors/type in new styles.

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — new button only in the app
// frontend/src/app/shared/my-button.ts

// ✅ GOOD — primitive in library, app imports it
// frontend/libs/forjd-ui/src/lib/button/button.ts
// frontend/libs/forjd-ui/src/public-api.ts → export { FjButton } ...
// app template: <forjd-button>...</forjd-button>
```

```scss
// ❌ BAD — app-only heading scale for reusable type
// frontend/src/styles/_headings.scss (used across pages)

// ✅ GOOD — typography tokens/styles in forjd-ui, app imports library styles
```
